1. Consider a sample of data from the Jackson Heart Study. In this problem, we will be examining body mass index (BMI; kg/m2) as a function of health as categorized by physical activity (PA3cat; Ideal Health, Intermediate Health, and Poor Health).

# clear environment
rm(list = ls())
# import data
data <- as_tibble(gsheet2tbl("https://docs.google.com/spreadsheets/d/1H3TP-2SBMGleriJLESOe1cdCjtSj2F76bUh5iBqC8tI/edit#gid=2142000894"))
# clean data
clean_data <- data %>% 
  select(BMI, BMI3cat) %>% 
  drop_na()

# ---CUSTOM COLORS---
custom_green_dark = "#71CA97"
custom_green_light = "#DeF7E9"
custom_gray = "#3D3D3D"
custom_orange = "#FC7307"
custom_purple = "#5A18C9"
# custom_tan_light = "#F7E3D4"
custom_red_light = "#F7D0C7"
custom_red_dark = "#F1917C"
# custom_density_hue = c(custom_purple,custom_orange)
# ---FUNCTIONS---
# f00 - Change default table format
change_table_format <- function(data_table){
  # local variables
  first_column <- data_table[1]
  dataframe_length <- NCOL(data_table)
  # format
  formattable(data_table, align = c("l",rep("c", dataframe_length - 1)),
              list(first_column = formatter("span", style = ~ style(color = custom_gray, font.weight = "bold")),
              area(row = 1, col = 2:dataframe_length) ~ color_tile(custom_green_light, custom_green_dark),
              area(row = 3, col = 2:dataframe_length) ~ color_tile(custom_red_light, custom_red_dark)
              )#/end list
              )#/end formattable
}
# f01 - get custom summary statistics
# !! sym() creates a symbol from a string
get_custom_summary <- function(data_table, category, values){
  summary <- data_table %>%
    group_by(!! sym(category)) %>% 
    summarise(Avg = mean(!! sym(values)),
              Median = median(!! sym(values)),
              SD = sd(!! sym(values)),
              Min = min(!! sym(values)),
              Max = max(!! sym(values)),
              IQRange = IQR(!! sym(values))
              )
    return(summary)
}

b. Use ANOVA to determine if there is a difference in BMI between the three levels of health as categorized by physical activity. Test at the \(\alpha=0.05\) level.

# One-way ANOVA
# Null Hypothesis:
# - H0: All means of observations grouped by BMI category are the same
# - H1: At least one category is different

h1 <- aov(clean_data$BMI ~ clean_data$BMI3cat)
summary(h1)
                     Df Sum Sq Mean Sq F value Pr(>F)    
clean_data$BMI3cat    2  76958   38479    1966 <2e-16 ***
Residuals          2646  51780      20                   
---
Signif. codes:  0 '***' 0.001 '**' 0.01 '*' 0.05 '.' 0.1 ' ' 1

Hypothesis

  • \(H_0\): \(\mu Ideal = \mu Intermediate\ = \mu Poor\)
  • \(H_1\): at least one is different

Test Statistic

  • \(F_0 = 1966\)

p-Value

  • \(p < 0.001\)

Conclusion

Reject \(H_0\) at the \(\alpha\)=0.05 level. There is sufficient evidence to suggest that there is a difference in BMI between the three levels of health.

c.Â Use the Kruskal-Wallis to determine if there is a difference in BMI between the three levels of health as categorized by physical activity (PA3cat; Ideal Health, Intermediate Health, and Poor Health). Test at the \(\alpha=0.05\) level.

kruskal.test(clean_data$BMI ~ clean_data$BMI3cat)

    Kruskal-Wallis rank sum test

Kruskal-Wallis chi-squared = 2129.4, df = 2, p-value < 2.2e-16

Hypothesis: Kruskal-Wallis

  • \(H_0\): \(M_{Ideal} = M_{Intermediate} = M_{Poor}\)
  • \(H_1\): at least one group is different

Test Statistic

  • \(H = 2129.4\)

p-Value

  • \(p < 0.001\)

Conclusion

Reject \(H_0\) at the \(\alpha\)=0.05 level. There is sufficient evidence to suggest that there is a difference in BMI between the three levels of health.

d.Â State/explain the ANOVA assumptions and assess them. Remember to state your conclusion (that you either meet the ANOVA assumptions or you do not).

We are unwilling to assume normality because we have found the assumption of normality invalid in diagnostic checks. We have performed the following ANOVA assumptions:

  1. Independence â the observations in each group need to be independent of each other. The data provided meets this requirement.

  2. Normality â the dependent variable should be approximately normally distributed for each combination of the groups. However, the residuals are not normally distributed; thus, we cannot assume normality.

# 2. Normality check
plot(h1)

boxplot(clean_data$BMI ~ clean_data$BMI3cat)

  1. Equal Variance - the variances for each group are equal or approximately equal. Since the p-value < 0.001 which is lower than our 0.05 level of significance, we cannot assume equality of variances.

g. Write a brief paragraph describing the results of your analysis. Include summary statistics, results of your chosen hypothesis test from part (e), results of the posthoc test in part (f), and a graph to help convey the results.

Analisis

The ANOVA assumptions were invalid after normality checks and Leveneâs test. Therefore, to find a statistically significant difference in BMI between the three levels of health (poor, intermediate, and ideal), a nonparametric Kruskal-Wallis test was conducted. The procedure following a Kruskal-Wallis test was to performed a Dunnâs posthoc test. All three levels of health grouped by BMI were significantly different from each other. Poor health was the dominant group.

Summary Statistics

To better understood the data, we calculated the mean, median, and standard deviation.

BMI3cat Avg Median SD Min Max IQRange
Ideal Health 22.78914 23.34 1.798843 18.53 25.00 2.42
Intermediate Health 27.60544 27.62 1.413412 25.00 29.99 2.53
Poor Health 36.63521 35.06 5.845224 30.00 59.57 6.68

ANOVA Assumptions

We were unwilling to assume normality because we have found the assumption of normality invalid in diagnostic checks. We have performed the following ANOVA assumptions:

1. Independence â the observations in each group need to be independent of each other. The data provided met this requirement.

2. Normality â the dependent variable should be approximately normally distributed for each combination of the groups. However, the residuals are not normally distributed; thus, normality was not assumed.

The Fitted vs.Â Residuals graph showed how the scatterplots had differences in size among the groups.

The QQ (quantile-quantile) plot did not display the normality of residuals. The scatterplots did not follow the 45-degree line.

Moreover, a boxplot displayed the distribution of BMI health for each group.

3. Equal Variance - the variances for each group are equal or approximately equal.

Since the p-value < 0.001 was lower than 0.05 level of significance, we did not assume equality of variances.

      2646

Kruskal-Wallis Test


    Kruskal-Wallis rank sum test

Hypothesis:

  • \(H_0\): \(M_{Ideal} = M_{Intermediate} = M_{Poor}\)
  • \(H_1\): at least one group is different

Test Statistic

  • \(H = 2129.4\)

p-Value

  • \(p < 0.001\)

Conclusion

Reject \(H_0\) at the \(\alpha\)=0.05 level. There was sufficient evidence to suggest that there was a difference in BMI between the three levels of health.

2. Again, consider the sample of data from the JHS. In this problem, we will be examining systolic blood pressure (sbp; mmHg) as a function of health as categorized by body mass index (BMI3cat; Ideal Health, Intermediate Health, and Poor Health), smoking status (everSmoker; 0=never smoker, 1=former or current smoker), and the interaction between health as categorized by body mass index and smoking status.

blood_data <- data %>% 
  select(BMI3cat, BMI, everSmoker) %>% 
  drop_na()

b. Use ANOVA to determine if there is a difference in systolic blood pressure between health as categorized by body mass index, smoking status, and the interaction between health as categorized by body mass index and smoking status. Test at the \(\alpha=0.05\) level. Remember to remove the interaction term if appropriate to do so.

# Two-way ANOVA with Interaction
# Null Hypothesis:
# - H1: The means of observations grouped by BMI are the same
# - H2: The means of observations grouped by Smoking are the same
# - H3: There is no interaction between BMI and Smoking

summary(h3_interaction <- aov(blood_data$BMI ~ blood_data$BMI3cat * factor(blood_data$everSmoker)))
                                                   Df Sum Sq Mean Sq  F value
blood_data$BMI3cat                                  2  76919   38459 1973.040

Residuals                                        2639  51441      19         
                                                 Pr(>F)    
blood_data$BMI3cat                               <2e-16 ***
factor(blood_data$everSmoker)                    0.0014 **

Residuals

Signif. codes:  0 '***' 0.001 '**' 0.01 '*' 0.05 '.' 0.1 ' ' 1

Reject H1. Reject H2. Keep H3.

After removing the interaction term, the ANOVA table was reconstructed.
